list.item:
The main source for the first part of the work (the universal history)
		is Bede, De sex aetatibus mundi,
		integrated mostly with
		Eutropius, Breviarium ab urbe condita;
		Orosius, Historia adversum paganos; 
		Paul the Deacon, Historia Romana;
		Jerome's Chronicon and Commentary on Daniel;
		the Liber Pontificalis and
		Bonizo of Sutri (see Matthew 1981, 245 n. 2);

For the digression on Franks and Lombards, the main sources are
		Paul the Deacon, Historia Langobardorum
		with the related Continuatio Casinensis;
		Gregory of Tours, Historia Francorum;
		Einhard, Vita Karoli;
		Aimoin of Fleury and his continuation
		(see Matthew 1981, 245 n. 3);

div.p:
It is not the task of this introduction to examine in depth the question of the authorship of the Chronicon. However, I will shortly summarize the issue. The attribution of the work to Romualdus Salernitanus is based on two textual notes in the handwritten tradition:
a sentence in manuscript C (Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale, Latinus 4933), not present in the other main manuscripts, probably a marginal note that later entered the text: "Ab hoc loco adiunctum est huic chronice per Romualdum secundum Salernatanum archiepiscopum". The note (not included in the text of my edition) is in par. g213.1-213.8, precisely in page 213, line 5 of Garufi, between "...iuramentum accepit" and "Dux autem Wilhelmus..." (events of year 1125). Garufi reports the note in apparatus (see Matthew 1981, 255-256 and Zabbia 2004, 382, 388 and footnote 5);
a second sentence in par. g293.39-294.2: "Hec autem omnia, que prediximus, ita gesta fuisse, nulli dubitationis uel incredulitatis scrupulum moueant, quia Romoaldus secundus Salernitanus archiepiscopus, qui uidit et interfuit, scripsit hec; et sciatis, quia uerum est testimonium eius" (see Mattew 1981, 239-240). With "hec... omnia, que prediximus", the text refers to the Peace of Venice.

Zabbia's arguments on authorship balance out those of Matthew. This leaves the question open, at least for the part of the work before year 1125. While internal evidence is not conclusive, the two notes mentioned above suggest quite clearly that:
The final part of the work – the account of the Peace of Venice – was almost certainly either written by Romualdus himself, or under his supervision (see second note above);
the section from year 1125 (par. g213.1-213.8) to the Peace of Venice was added, 'adiunctum' by Romualdus as well (see first note);
the section from Adam to year 1125 constituted something that existed before Romualdus (see note in g213.1-213.8: "adiunctum est huic chronice").

The three oldest witnesses of the work are:


A: Vaticanus Latinus 3973, of the late XII century, available in

			https://digi.vatlib.it/mss/detail/Vat.lat.3973;
		III manifest in

			https://digi.vatlib.it/iiif/MSS_Vat.lat.3973/manifest.json;


B: Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana, Archivio di San Pietro, E 22,
		of the XIV century, available in

			http://digi.vatlib.it/mss/detail/Arch.Cap.S.Pietro.E.22;
		III manifest in

			https://digi.vatlib.it/iiif/MSS_Arch.Cap.S.Pietro.E.22/manifest.json;


C: Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale, Latinus 4933,
		of the late XII-early XIII century, available in

			https://archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cc63823p.

A detailed description and discussion of the manuscript tradition can be found in
	Garufi, XXXI-XXXVI; Hoffmann 1967, 156-165 (mostly on MS A);
	Matthew 1981, 241-242; Zabbia 2004, 385-388;
	Zabbia 2006 and Zabbia 2010, 24-25

The 'p' elements including these additions have been marked with attribute
	@decls="#longversion", in this XML file, linking to the relevant
	'editorialDecl'.

I transcribed A and O in TEI XML
using Garufi or Bonetti as noted above,
then performed an automatic collation of the transcriptions using
juxtacommons.org and edited the XML output files file manually.
I divided the text in four parts for collation:


for part '1' (incipit to g163.1-163.5), I collated Garufi against A;

for part '2-alfa' (g163.6-163.7 through g167.4-168.4), Bonetti against A;

for part '2-bravo' (g168.5-168.7 through g185.8-186.5), I collated Bonetti, A and O;

for part '2-charlie' (g186.6-186.7 to the end), Bonetti against A.

The OCR files of print editions and the transcriptions of manuscripts have been marked according to module '11 Representation of Primary Sources' of TEI P5. Provided that quite surprisingly, there are yet no collation tools that compare XML trees, i.e. that compare TEI transcriptions taking the markup into account, I had to normalize the TEI transcriptions to prepare them for collation with juxtacommons.org. I normalized transcriptions through custom Python scripts, which:
extracted an 'alphabetic' transcription from those paragraphs that had been transcribed he graphematic layer;
deleted the following tags with their textual content: 'interp', 'abbr', 'surplus', 'note', 'milestone'.
normalized numerals, e.g. 'xiiii' from MS A to 'XIV';
introduced standard text for gaps in the MSS, e.g. {Gap in the MS: 1 illegible word};
chose between 'sic'/'corr', 'reg'/'orig' elements;
in particular, regularized 'j' to 'i' and 'v' to 'u' in all print and handwritten sources;
capitalized proper nouns and words at the beginning of sentences also for MS text (e.g. 'pompeius' from MS A to 'Pompeius');
stripped the markup for the following TEI tags (keeping their textual content, if any): 'rs', 'hi', 'w', 'choice', 'orig', 'reg', 'num', 'subst', 'add', 'del', 'expan', 'sic', 'seg', 'lb', 'pb', 'quote', 'title', 'said', 'soCalled', 'surplus', 'supplied', 'gap', 'l';
replaced XML angle brackets with [square brackets] for 'p' start- and end-tags, thus producing an output such as [p xml:id="g3.2-3.6"]: another script then restored the angle brackets in the output of the juxtacommons.org collation;

In combination with each @type, @subtype can take one of the following values:
In combination with @type='substantive', @subtype (if present) can be: 'missing-in-print', 'num-num', 'missing-in-ms', 'transposition', 'fs';
In combination with @type='orthographic': 'y' (e.g. martirio/martyrio), 'v', 'j', 'ae', 'h' (e.g. hodie/odie), 'n-pn', 'hi-y', 'num-word' (e.g. III/tria), 'case', 'tc' (e.g. iustitia/iusticia), 'double' (e.g. successit/succesit), 'ph', 'cq', 'mpn', 'tz', 'cz', 'ck', 'word-segmentation', 'ch', ', 'dm-mm', 'mn', 'ncx';
In combination with @type="punctuation": "change-punctuation", "add-punctuation", "remove-punctuation".

In orthographic variants (i.e. 'app' elements with type="orthography), I generally tended not to modify the print edition spelling. I did modify it, mostly by adopting MS A's spelling, in cases in which
the print edition has an evident typo, which the MS does not have (e.g. 'eorem' Garufi / 'eorum MS A in g26.12-26.23);
the MS's form clearly is more standard both in classical dieval Latin and, most of all, more adherent to the usus scribendi of the rest of the work (e.g. 'espers' in Garufi / 'expers' in A, or omicidia G / homicidia A);
the print edition has a classical diphthong ('ae' or 'oe') while the MS has the monophthongized spelling, which I preferred, since monophthongized forms are standard in the text. For example, in g70.1-70.19 I chose A's 'Rome' over Garufi's 'Romae'. This is a sub-case of the previous principle, and in 'ae'/'e' variants it is marked with @subtype='ae';
I eliminated a dash distinguishing a composed word in the print edition (e.g. in g80.1-80.4 I chose spelling 'Primiscrinium' over 'Primi-scrinium' of Garufi).
